722238f-a.text:
Park Avenue, north from and including 51st Street, showing buildings along the west side, also the parks in the center, shaved to make room for more traffic.

The five story building between 52nd and 53rd Street is the Racquet and Tennis Club, and behind it on the horizon rises the Tower of the Fuller Building at Madison Ave and 57th St.

The small buildings in the block above, 53rd to 54th St, are much older then their surroundings, dating back to at least 1890s.

On the east side, just north of St. Bartholomew's, is the Hotel Ambassador.

Summer 1929

722247f-a.text:
A general view of the Grand Central 2one as viewed southward on Park Ave. from East 52nd Street, at which point appears the Hotel Ambassador (left foreground) with St. Bartholomew's P.E. Church just beyond (S.E. corner of 51et Street). Prominently shown (centre) is the new Waldorf Astoria Hotel flanked on one side by the R.C.A. Building and the Chrysler, Chanin, Grand Central Palace and Lincoln Buildings on the other. Distinctly shown between the R.C.A. Building and the Waldorf Astoria Hotel is Tudor City located near the East River, which is dimly
apparent on the left.
October 31, 1932.
